my ‘concealing abuse’ video.

00:16:52.220 --> 00:16:56.780
What that video doesn’t mention is a particular
exception to the policy

00:16:56.780 --> 00:17:00.220
one of special relevance to the Royal Commission.

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:03.620
Witnesses are told that when they take any
oath to tell the truth

00:17:03.620 --> 00:17:08.250
or are placed on a witness stand, they’re
obligated to speak the truth

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:10.270
if they speak at all.

00:17:10.270 --> 00:17:13.280
In these circumstances,
the only option they have

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:16.140
other than to speak the truth,
is to remain silent.

00:17:16.140 --> 00:17:19.050
It’ll become clear that even this rule was
flouted

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:22.180
by Jehovah’s Witnesses during the Commission
hearing.

00:17:22.180 --> 00:17:27.040
It’ll also become increasingly clear just
how far down in their list of priorities

00:17:27.050 --> 00:17:31.320
came the welfare of the children they were
supposed to protect.

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:35.230
Horley and Jackson’s letter about Bill Neill
to the branch office stated:

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:40.500
‘We recommended to him that he step down
as an elder’ and that ‘He agreed to this.’

00:17:40.500 --> 00:17:43.250
Stewart put it to Horley that it seemed they
had offered Neill

00:17:43.250 --> 00:17:48.150
a chance to step down voluntarily, rather
than be forcibly removed.

00:17:48.150 --> 00:17:52.900
Horley denied this, claiming it was just an
unfortunate choice of words.

00:17:52.900 --> 00:17:57.880
But those unfortunate words were consistent
with BCB’s previous testimony

00:17:57.880 --> 00:18:00.630
that Neill had merely stepped down.

00:18:00.630 --> 00:18:03.070
In the same letter, Horley and Jackson added

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:07.210
that they felt no further action or restrictions
need apply.

00:18:07.210 --> 00:18:08.950
This meant Neill was free to participate

00:18:08.950 --> 00:18:12.620
in all the same church and Bible study meetings
as before

00:18:12.620 --> 00:18:18.080
including meetings at his home which BCB was
expected to attend.

00:18:18.080 --> 00:18:22.280
The letter went on to make the bizarrely premature
recommendation

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:25.270
that once the matter had died down, Neill
should be recommended

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:30.140
as an elder again so he could help the congregation
as he’d done in the past.

00:18:30.140 --> 00:18:33.300
Stewart asked Horley if
by the phrase ‘dying down’

00:18:33.310 --> 00:18:36.620
he meant once the controversy has abated.

00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:41.840
Horley claimed that the term ‘dying down’
was another case of unfortunate wording.

00:18:41.840 --> 00:18:44.560
When Stewart then suggested that Horley’s
prime concern

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:48.060
was about Neill’s reputation, he initially
rejected the idea.

00:18:48.060 --> 00:18:50.490
But Stewart continued along this line

00:18:50.490 --> 00:18:54.410
suggesting that Horley’s concern was about
the functioning of his organisation

00:18:54.410 --> 00:18:58.040
and not about the protection of children in
his congregation.

00:18:58.040 --> 00:18:59.780
Horley agreed.

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:04.660
When Stewart put it to him his concern wasn’t
about what support he could offer BCB.

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:08.260
Horley admitted that while that had ‘some
bearing’ for him

00:19:08.260 --> 00:19:12.020
it was more about Neill’s qualifications
to teach.

00:19:12.020 --> 00:19:15.420
It was a stunning confession.

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:17.800
Towards the end of his period in the witness stand

00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:21.530
Horley was given a detailed account of BCB’s abuse.

00:19:21.530 --> 00:19:25.160
He hadn’t known about any of it and said
it came as a shock to him.

00:19:25.160 --> 00:19:28.570
He was asked if he thought the fact it was
only coming to light now

00:19:28.570 --> 00:19:33.760
had something to do with the process he engaged
in when BCB made the initial complaint

00:19:33.760 --> 00:19:37.120
a process in which she had to make her allegations
to her abuser

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:40.970
and an elder who she knew was friends with
her abuser.

00:19:40.970 --> 00:19:43.570
He said he could see the point being made.

00:19:43.570 --> 00:19:47.560
When it was suggested BCB needed a more nurturing
supportive environment

00:19:47.560 --> 00:19:50.060
to make a full disclosure, he agreed.

00:19:50.060 --> 00:19:54.390
But when asked if he had any thoughts on what
the organisation should do about it

00:19:54.390 --> 00:19:58.400
he reverted to compliant form, saying he had
no comments

00:19:58.400 --> 00:20:01.440
he just followed the procedures.

00:20:05.020 --> 00:20:08.760
What came across from the many elders called
to testify at the Commission

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:11.330
was that they were so immersed in procedure

00:20:11.330 --> 00:20:14.500
they failed to consider the accuser’s experience.

00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:18.900
Doug Jackson’s responses clearly illustrated
this lack of empathy.

00:20:18.900 --> 00:20:21.260
When it was put to Jackson that BCB was unaware

00:20:21.260 --> 00:20:23.540
of the purpose of the meetings she was attending

00:20:23.540 --> 00:20:25.760
initially he flat-out rejected the idea.

00:20:25.770 --> 00:20:28.460
But Stewart took some time to remind him

00:20:28.460 --> 00:20:32.540
that as an elder he had knowledge not given
to the congregation

00:20:32.540 --> 00:20:37.860
knowledge of judicial procedures, standards
of evidence and punitive measures.

00:20:37.860 --> 00:20:42.580
Stewart then asked Jackson if he’d accept
BCB wouldn’t know about these things.

00:20:42.580 --> 00:20:45.620
Jackson changed his ‘no’ to a ‘maybe’.

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:49.300
Stewart asked if Jackson could see how this
lack of transparency

00:20:49.300 --> 00:20:53.650
would’ve left BCB in a position of vulnerability
and confusion.

00:20:53.650 --> 00:20:56.220
Jackson said he did now.

00:20:56.220 --> 00:20:59.750
Stewart repeated to Jackson the portion of
BCB’s statement

00:20:59.750 --> 00:21:02.520
in which she was asked in one of the judicial meetings

00:21:02.520 --> 00:21:04.500
whether she had anything more to tell

00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:09.540
and she falsely responded ‘No’ because
of various inhibiting factors.

00:21:09.540 --> 00:21:12.520
These included talking in front of a room
full of men

00:21:12.530 --> 00:21:18.240
talking in front of her abuser and being afraid
of the consequences of telling the truth.

00:21:18.240 --> 00:21:21.770
Jackson accepted that talking about her abuse
to a room full of men

00:21:21.770 --> 00:21:24.760
would’ve been very hard for BCB

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:27.340
as would talking in front of her abuser.

00:21:27.340 --> 00:21:31.160
But when it was put to him that BCB didn’t
feel it was a safe environment

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:33.720
he said he didn’t know why she would’ve
felt that

00:21:33.720 --> 00:21:36.010
because they tried to comfort her.

00:21:36.010 --> 00:21:39.690
He seemed unable to comprehend that his supposed
efforts to comfort BCB

00:21:39.690 --> 00:21:44.560
weren’t enough to magically overcome all
the intimidating factors she identified.

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:47.760
Instead of admitting that he had failed to
comfort her

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:51.960
his instinct was instead to insinuate that
the failure was hers

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:55.160
she had failed to receive the comfort he offered.

00:21:55.160 --> 00:22:00.980
This kind of mindset is common in high-control
groups that deny individuality.

00:22:00.980 --> 00:22:06.740
Members are slotted into fixed procedures
and expected to give fixed reactions.

00:22:06.740 --> 00:22:10.780
When they don’t, the fault is with them
— not the procedure.

00:22:10.780 --> 00:22:15.000
McClellan put it to Jackson that the organisation’s
investigative process

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.420
inflicted further trauma on BCB.

00:22:18.420 --> 00:22:22.870
Jackson said he understood that now — but
hadn’t appreciated it at the time.

00:22:22.870 --> 00:22:27.060
It’s instructive to reflect on the reflex
dismissiveness of the elders

00:22:27.060 --> 00:22:30.030
who testified at the Commission whenever it
was suggested

00:22:30.030 --> 00:22:35.300
that the abused individuals in their care
felt unsafe or unsupported.

00:22:35.300 --> 00:22:41.140
Judge McClellan and assisting counsel Stewart
were two highly skilled communicators.

00:22:41.150 --> 00:22:44.030
They also wielded the power of the legal system.

00:22:44.030 --> 00:22:49.040
But even they had to repeatedly spend exhausting
swathes of time

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:51.690
walking the elders through their own procedures

00:22:51.690 --> 00:22:56.320
trying to get them to empathise with the experiences
of those abused individuals.

00:22:56.320 --> 00:22:59.090
If, with their considerable skill and power

00:22:59.090 --> 00:23:02.940
they had to work this hard to break through
the elders’ dismissiveness

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:05.650
what chance did an unskilled powerless member

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:10.460
of a Jehovah’s Witness congregation have
of making themselves heard?

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:16.840
Another elder concerned with reputation was
Joe Bello

00:23:16.840 --> 00:23:19.980
one of the elders BCB wrote to years after
the abuse

00:23:19.990 --> 00:23:23.180
in an effort to protect other children from
Bill Neill.

00:23:23.180 --> 00:23:26.380
Asked about whether he would ever report a
matter to the police

00:23:26.390 --> 00:23:30.650
Bello fell back on the mantra-like evasion
given by the other elders:

00:23:30.650 --> 00:23:32.800
he’d contact the branch.

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:36.340
Bello confirmed BCB’s account that when
her husband had mentioned

00:23:36.350 --> 00:23:38.570
they were thinking of talking to the Royal
Commission

00:23:38.570 --> 00:23:40.660
Bello had asked what that could accomplish

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:43.840
other than dragging Jehovah’s name through
the mud.

00:23:43.840 --> 00:23:45.900
It was put to him that this would be understood

00:23:45.900 --> 00:23:48.900
as a discouragement against going to the Commission.

00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:53.200
He said that wasn’t how it was meant — he
was just thinking aloud.

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:56.180
Although Bello initially seemed to regret
his words

00:23:56.180 --> 00:23:58.250
and reflected that he shouldn’t have said them

00:23:58.250 --> 00:24:01.760
he then revealed that he stood by the underlying
sentiment.

00:24:01.760 --> 00:24:07.200
Stewart asked him if, within his faith, Jehovah
was considered a loving god.

00:24:07.200 --> 00:24:10.980
When Bello confirmed this, Stewart asked if
Jehovah would not also then

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:15.180
be more concerned about the victim than his
own name.

00:24:15.180 --> 00:24:20.360
Defiantly, Bello replied: ‘Jehovah would
be concerned about the victim

00:24:20.360 --> 00:24:23.900
but Jehovah is concerned about his own name too.’

00:24:23.900 --> 00:24:28.120
Judge McClellan asked Bello if he’d been
following the work of the Royal Commission.

00:24:28.130 --> 00:24:31.190
Bello hadn’t — despite knowing a couple
of months previously

00:24:31.190 --> 00:24:33.410
that he would have to give evidence.

00:24:33.410 --> 00:24:36.470
He said he might’ve scanned the headlines
of the Saturday paper

00:24:36.470 --> 00:24:39.710
but he didn’t watch the news or listen to
the radio.

00:24:39.710 --> 00:24:44.140
His complete lack of interest in the Commission’s
work was abundantly clear

00:24:44.140 --> 00:24:47.050
and consistent with the apathy exhibited

00:24:47.050 --> 00:24:51.360
by most of the witnesses testifying for the
organisation.

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:57.700
Doctor Monica Applewhite was paid by the organisation

00:24:57.710 --> 00:25:01.000
to be an expert witness in its defence.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:05.660
Applewhite presented herself as an independent
consultant in child sexual abuse

00:25:05.660 --> 00:25:08.370
visiting institutes to make risk assessments

00:25:08.370 --> 00:25:11.760
and develop educational programs and policies.

00:25:11.760 --> 00:25:14.800
This included assessing how they prevented abuse;

00:25:14.800 --> 00:25:16.940
how they responded to warning signs;

00:25:16.940 --> 00:25:19.650
how they responded to disclosures of abuse;

00:25:19.650 --> 00:25:22.040
and how they remedied the situation.

00:25:22.040 --> 00:25:26.020
Applewhite was an unexpected choice of champion
for the Jehovah’s Witnesses

00:25:26.020 --> 00:25:28.620
because she was an active member
of the Catholic church

00:25:28.620 --> 00:25:32.560
which the organisation has repeatedly dismissed
as a false religion

00:25:32.560 --> 00:25:35.400
characterised as an enemy of true worship

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:41.380
criticised for its political meddling and
slated for its handling of child sexual abuse.

00:25:41.380 --> 00:25:44.200
Leaving aside the strangeness of this alliance

00:25:44.200 --> 00:25:46.920
Applewhite’s testimony was a mess.

00:25:46.920 --> 00:25:49.460
Stewart and McClellan noted that many opinions

00:25:49.460 --> 00:25:52.400
offered in her report had no source references.

00:25:52.400 --> 00:25:54.780
Applewhite said she was already fully scheduled

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:56.640
when she started working on the report

00:25:56.640 --> 00:25:59.900
so she hadn’t been conscientious about her
citations.

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:03.700
In fact what emerged from Applewhite’s report
and testimony

00:26:03.700 --> 00:26:06.070
was that her so-called expert evidence

00:26:06.070 --> 00:26:10.360
consisted of browsing online material from
the organisation’s own website

00:26:10.360 --> 00:26:13.680
and speaking to staff from its legal branch.

00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:16.160
She said she hadn’t reviewed any specific cases

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:17.980
and couldn’t offer any opinion

00:26:17.980 --> 00:26:21.240
on whether the implementation
of the organisation’s policies

00:26:21.240 --> 00:26:23.740
had resulted in law-abiding responses

00:26:23.740 --> 00:26:27.980
good practice of child protection
or compassionate care.

00:26:27.980 --> 00:26:32.900
As Stewart noted, all she’d basically done
was a documentary review.

00:26:32.900 --> 00:26:35.200
Applewhite showed a distinct lack of awareness

00:26:35.210 --> 00:26:38.420
of the power relationship between elders and
congregation members

00:26:38.420 --> 00:26:41.230
erroneously stating that elders were merely viewed

00:26:41.230 --> 00:26:44.400
as ‘fellow workers’ by the congregation.

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:47.440
As Stewart pointed out, elders were very clearly
characterised

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:50.480
by the organisation as shepherds over the flock.

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:53.560
Their privilege and authority was reinforced
by the belief

00:26:53.560 --> 00:26:56.840
that elders were directly appointed by the
Holy Spirit

00:26:56.840 --> 00:26:59.500
another fact of which she was unaware.

00:26:59.500 --> 00:27:01.580
Applewhite stated there was no requirement

00:27:01.580 --> 00:27:05.500
for elders or ministerial servants to be alone
with children.

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:09.560
But Stewart produced a branch document directed
to all elders

00:27:09.560 --> 00:27:14.000
stating that elders and ministerial servants
are put in a position of trust

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:19.340
that explicitly included being more liberal
about leaving children in their care.

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:22.360
Applewhite was also unaware of the fact that
abused individuals

00:27:22.360 --> 00:27:26.680
were cautioned not to reveal facts about the
congregation in group therapy.

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:29.780
The only stipulation she’d heard in regards
to therapy

00:27:29.780 --> 00:27:32.440
was that the organisation recommended choosing
someone

00:27:32.440 --> 00:27:34.980
who respected their religious beliefs.

00:27:34.980 --> 00:27:38.980
As the facts about the actual experience of
abused individuals emerged

00:27:38.980 --> 00:27:40.360
Applewhite began to withdraw

00:27:40.360 --> 00:27:44.100
some of her poorly considered support for
the organisation.

00:27:44.100 --> 00:27:46.280
She announced that if it turned out that people

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:50.810
had to confront their abusers and had to sit
in the room with no support

00:27:50.810 --> 00:27:53.780
that would not meet the standards of care.

00:27:53.780 --> 00:27:57.540
She conceded she hadn’t understood that
that was the process.

00:27:57.540 --> 00:28:00.260
Applewhite stated that when somebody abuses

00:28:00.260 --> 00:28:04.880
and their internal mechanisms of control had
allowed them to cross that line once

00:28:04.880 --> 00:28:09.720
she didn’t have confidence in those internal
mechanisms of control for the future.

00:28:09.720 --> 00:28:13.820
As such, she suggested that the risk
of re-offence was great

00:28:13.820 --> 00:28:16.920
and agreed that positive steps needed to be taken

00:28:16.920 --> 00:28:19.640
to ensure that such a person didn’t have access

00:28:19.650 --> 00:28:22.350
or the opportunity to abuse again.

00:28:22.350 --> 00:28:25.350
She said there should be strong and cooperative
relationships

00:28:25.350 --> 00:28:27.390
with child protection authorities

00:28:27.390 --> 00:28:29.880
but had no awareness of the difficult relationship

00:28:29.880 --> 00:28:34.040
the Jehovah’s Witness organisation had with
secular authorities.

00:28:34.040 --> 00:28:38.620
The Commission didn’t consider that Applewhite’s
report had assisted their enquiry

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:41.340
and rejected her opinions on numerous grounds

00:28:41.340 --> 00:28:44.410
including lack of evidence or citations

00:28:44.410 --> 00:28:47.660
but most damningly, because she’d failed
to investigate

00:28:47.660 --> 00:28:51.660
the experiences of a single survivor of child
sexual abuse

00:28:51.660 --> 00:28:55.940
whose complaint was dealt with by the Jehovah’s
Witness organisation.

00:28:55.940 --> 00:28:57.950
By the end of this first case

00:28:57.950 --> 00:29:02.290
the Royal Commission had already gathered
confirmation of unthinkable negligence

00:29:02.290 --> 00:29:05.350
deeply inappropriate and traumatising procedures

00:29:05.350 --> 00:29:10.750
and a cover-up mentality that elevated reputation
far above the protection of children

00:29:10.750 --> 00:29:16.500
and led to the use of shaming tactics on abused
individuals to try and silence them.

00:29:16.500 --> 00:29:20.460
From this atrocious start, things would only
get worse.

00:29:20.460 --> 00:29:22.180
As I’ll be showing in part two

00:29:22.180 --> 00:29:27.320
shocking new levels of deception and corruption
within the organisation would be laid bare

00:29:27.330 --> 00:29:31.620
including evidence that some elders had stooped
to breaking their own rules

00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:34.920
in order to avoid exposing abuse.

